@node intro "Introduction"

Max's BBS Professional was originally created to add extra power to Max's 
v1.54 as well as add extra support for programmers to create more advanced
doors :)

Now it has turned into a monster!  Sporting one of the most advanced file
description system EVER seen on the miggy!  As well as supporting things
that even expensive commercial packages can't! :)))

@endnode
@node sysreq "System Requirements"

Obviously, you need to already have a copy of Max's BBS v1.54 installed :)

All features auto-detect the OS version, but you will need v39 of the 
Asl.Library (OS3.x) to use the screen mode requester in the config editor.

It also helps to have a fast miggy with tons of memory :)))

@endnode
@node inst "Installation & Configs"

Installation
~~~~~~~~~~~~

Installing Mp2 is relatively painless :))))

Just de-archive to BBS: and it takes care of the rest!

You also need to double click on Create.exe to finish off the installation 
tho.


Configuring The Filebase
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The new Mp2 requires several text lines to be set up/altered!

These are lines 155, 166, 320, 321, 322, 323, 324, 326, 327, 328 and 329.

The descriptions of these are :-

155	- This replaces the (L) line to show a locked file.  This line is
	now use to show a FREE Download.  This is printed straight after
	the file description.
	
166	- This used to be the Max's file description line, now it's used
	for the File_ID entry ANSI.
	
320	- This is the "Uploaded By" text line, printed just before the
	name of the person who uploaded the file.  It is identical to the
	system used by Spin Diz.
	
321	- This text line is printed straight after the file uploader name!
	e.g.  File Upped By Niki Murkett.. Kewl eh?
	
322	- This line is printed after every page of files.  It's a dedicated
	file marker line, & should tell the user to press return to continue
	or [UP] to start marking files :)
	
323	- This text line is shown when Mp2 is just about to start scanning
	a file for a file description.
	
324	- Text line to be displayed when Mp2 has discovered a File_ID.

325	- INTERNAL USE - DO NOT PUT ANYTHING IN THIS LINE!  IT WILL BE NUKED!

326	- Text line to be displayed when a single line file comment (Such as
	an aminet Short: or an auto-nuke comment) is found.
	
327	- The file seperator bar.  This is displayed inbetween all files
	in the list.  Unless you leave it blank to disable, it *MUST* be
	1 line high ONLY!
	
328	- If no file description is found, but a personal logo is, then 
	this text line is displayed (Logo's are explained below)
	
329	- If a personal is displayed, this text line is printed to give
	the user an option to use the logo.

330	- File list header.  This is displayed at the start of any file 
	listing.

331	- Before download text.  This text line is printed just before the
	list of marked files is displayed.  You can use this to display
	byte ratio information.


Example IFF files are provided to help you set up the default config 
correctly :)

When set up, your file lister should look something like :-


=-=-=-=- tHIS fILE iS iN : Virus Checkers =-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
Xtruder36.lha       Xtruder 3.6 by Martin Wulffeld. This virus
                    killer can detect more than 250 filevira.
                    Has a screen mode- and font sensitive GUI
                    along with a comprehensive ARexx interface
                    and locale support.

                              WOAH!  A FREE DOWNLOAD!
              447930  07-Jul-97  23:01   -uPPED-bY- Niki Murkett !

[UP] Start Marking [RET] Continue File List [S] Stop



Logo's!
~~~~~~~

A logo is basically a half finished File_ID!  They contain a personal or
group logo, and if used, the person uploading only has to add a quick line
of text to finish the file_id off :)

Logo's are stored in BBS:Scripts/Logo/ and have the name of the user without
spaces.  e.g. My personal logo is called NikiMurkett & looks like...

          /\_____ ____/\__ ____/\
       ::/o      Vo       Vo     \:::
      :::||  .   |:   [___||  |   \:::
     ::::||  |   |___     ||       \:::
      :::|:  |   |   ]    |:  |    /::
       ::|___|__ |________| __|___/::
          ~~~~~~\|pRe$En7$|/~~~~~
  ]--------------------------------------[



Logo's are just pure text files!.  All you have to make sure of is that the
last line is a line of spaces!

Logo selector/designer doors for Mp2 will soon be released into PD.


Split File Ratios
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Max's Pro 2 uses a cheat method to achieve split file ratios.  In the 
sections configure window you will notice the Reply Acc gadget is now 
available on file sections.

This gadget is now used to determine the amount of file credits each file
in that section takes away.

Set to 0 to make a section free d/l, set to 1 for normal.

If you have a 10:1 file ratio system on your BBS yet want one section to
be 5:1 then you'd set the gadget to 2.  Thus halving the ratio purely on
that file section! :)


Byte Ratios
~~~~~~~~~~~

Byte ratios have been one of the most requested features for /X\2!  Here's
how to set them up (This IS required even if you don't use the /X\2 
filebase!!!)

In BBS:UserWorkFiles/ There is a file called Ratio.template...  The 
description of this file is:-

Line 1:-	Bytes uploaded
Line 2:-	Bytes downloaded
Line 3:-	Byte ratio
Line 4:-	Ratio type (0=Files only, 1=Bytes & Files, 2=Bytes ONLY)
Line 5:-	Free bytes

Lines 1 & 2 should be left at 0 for obvious reasons.
Line 3 should be set to a reasonable value.  Setting this to 10 gives a 
10:1 byte ratio lets a user download 10K for every 1K they upload :) Setting
to 0 disables the byte ratio system (Default)

Line 4 is the ratio type.  Setting to 0 disables the byte ratio calculations,
setting to 1 enables both ratio systems & setting to 2 means the normal file
is ignored in favour of the byte ratio.

Line 5 is how many free bytes a user is allowed.  Be generous in this if
you run an existing BBS!  Normal scene board give around 1MB free, but if
you already run a max's board then a value of 3-5MB is normal :)

The following auto-inserts are provided to aid you show a users byte ratio
info:-

%0	- Bytes Uploaded
%1	- Bytes Downloaded
%2	- Byte Ratio 	(Show Unlimited if 0)
%3	- Byte Ratio Type	(Shows File, Bytes + File or Bytes)
%4	- Free Bytes insert
%5	- Bytes available before upload insert.  The calculation is:-
	  (Bytes uploaded*Ratio)-Bytes Downloaded+Free Bytes.


User Directories
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

A new feature of /X\2 is User Directories.  These are created for each
user & have the following default layout:-

UserName
	System (dir)
	     AutoSend (dir)
	   ByteRatio.Data

The System directory by default contains the AutoSend dir & the byte ratio
info for the user.  The AutoSend dir contains any files the sysop wishes
to send to the user.

The system dir can also contain custom versions of the maindoor.text, or 
any of the door.text files.  These are checked for in preference of the
original copy in the doors: directory.


System Password
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

If you want to restrict access to your BBS then you can set a system 
password.  Just choose a short password & store it in a file called
Env:MaxsPro/SysPass  Or use the following command:-

Echo >Env:MaxsPro/Syspass "PASSWORD" NOLINE

Now a password is asked for before the login name.  Text line 332 is
displayed before the password is asked for.


@endnode

@node inuse "Starting up Max's Pro 2"

Starting Mp2
~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Mp2 can ONLY be run from the CLI!

It's started in the same way Max's is :-

BBS:MaxsPro2


There are however, a few new command line options supported by Mp2!

These are to do with running multiple copies of Mp2 using the same config
file!..  Max's requires you to use 1 config file for each node :(

All are optional unless you set Mp2 to Trapdoor mode (Explained later)

For a list of current command line options use BBS:MaxsPro2 ?


CONFIG "Maxsbbs.config"

Lets you choose the current configuration to load in.


DEVICE "serial.device"

This sets the serial device name that Mp2 should use...
This OVERRIDES the setting you have in your modem configure menu! :)


UNIT "0"

This sets which unit number to open the serial device on...  Replace the ?
with the correct unit number.  Eg.   UNIT 1 opens the serial device on unit 1.
This also overrides the setting in the modem configure menu!


SPAWN

This sets Mp2 to run in Trapdoor mode!  This mode is for when you want
Mp2 to run from a program that's already recieved & handled the call, such
as the Trapdoor mail frontend system or a Call-back/Voice Mail system :)

When in this mode, Mp2 will pass the caller straight on to the normal
login procedure & quit after the caller has logged off! :)

To use this function, you *MUST* have Auto-Connect ticked in the modem
configure window!!!!!!  You *MUST* also use the RATE option.


RATE "33600"

This param is used along side the SPAWN mode to set the rate at which the 
caller connected at!

Due to a side-effect in the Max's code, the caller has to hit a key before
Mp2 recieves the connect rate :/  Simply set the modem init string to 
something like...   Paused - [RET] Continue...

And then the user will hit return (Or ANY key will do!) and Mp2 will 
continue :)


NOSEARCH

Stops Mp2 searching through file_id's on a normal file search.  Useful if
you have a slow Amiga.


NOADAPT

Stops the main ansi screen auto-adapting to your screen size.  Use if you
get screen corruption!.


Examples
~~~~~~~~

Here's a few examples from a few setups I've used in the past.  They should
help you understand how the extra options work :)


{Script: Boot 3 telnet Nodes}

BBS:MaxsPro2 Device "telnetd.device" Unit 0
BBS:MaxsPro2 Device "telnetd.device" Unit 1
BBS:MaxsPro2 Device "telnetd.device" Unit 2

This will boot up 3 telnet nodes using my default MAXsBBS.config file! :)
As the normal options just override the config settings, they are perfect 
for multi-node BBS's! :)))


{Script: Boot BBS}

BBS:MaxsPro2 Device "hyperCOM3.device" Unit 0
BBS:MaxsPro2 Device "hyperCOM3.device" Unit 1
BBS:MaxsPro2 Device "BaudBandit.device" Unit 0

This is basically the script I use to start up my BBS! :)  Nodes 1 & 2 are
driven by a lurvly HyperCOM3 serial card (Worth its weight in GOLD!) while
node 3 is stuck on the crappy internal serial port....


Running from Trapdoor
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Here is a clip from my Trapdoor config...   I have to use a seperate config
for this to disable fidonet pickup, change the init string etc.

BBSMODE SPAWN
BBSCOMMAND "BBS:MAXsPro2 Spawn Rate "B" Config "BBS:MAXsTD.config"

This command line starts Mp2 in Trapdoor mode, sets the connect rate
(Trapdoor uses % codes to pass on parameters) and specifies a custom 
config to use :)

@endnode

@node filebase "Using the Max's Pro 2 Filebase"

Using the new Mp2 Filebase!
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Please excuse any mistakes in this bit!  It's 4 AM!  And I've been working
on these dox for 2 days solid now :/


Oki, the new features in the Mp2 filebase that you need to know about in
maintaining your BBS are local uploads, file_id editing & Free downloads!


File_ID editing
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Mp2 stores its file_id's as seperate text files in Diz:...  To edit these,
all you need is a ANSI/text editor!

If using an ANSI editor, you *MUST* use one that saves out as uncompressed
ANSI files!

Okay, File_ID's are stored in a special format in Mp2!  Normal File_ID's are
45x13 in size and the filebase processes each one before displaying to center
them on the screen.  Mp2 stores the first line like normal, but any lines
afterwards are indented inwards by 20 chars!

eg...

        ______
       |) oz .|          aUSTRALIAN       .
 .  ___||   ==(       nSA dESIGN gROUP    .
 . (_____/\/\_|                           :
 :     \|(oo)|/       pROULDY pRESENTS    !
 :     (  --  )                           |
 !    __\ <> /__         sUPER lOG        |
 |  _/ /"`--'"\ \                         |
 |_/  (_      _) \    sHOWS lAST cALLERS  |
 /  __ /      / __\_  aND uSER/bBS sTATS  |
 \_/  X mARTY )(___ \                     |
 `-\ /--------\_(___/--+61-3-9870-4393----'


After being processed, it becomes....


        ______
                           |) oz .|          aUSTRALIAN       .
                     .  ___||   ==(       nSA dESIGN gROUP    .
                     . (_____/\/\_|                           :
                     :     \|(oo)|/       pROULDY pRESENTS    !
                     :     (  --  )                           |
                     !    __\ <> /__         sUPER lOG        |
                     |  _/ /"`--'"\ \                         |
                     |_/  (_      _) \    sHOWS lAST cALLERS  |
                     /  __ /      / __\_  aND uSER/bBS sTATS  |
                     \_/  X mARTY )(___ \                     |
                     `-\ /--------\_(___/--+61-3-9870-4393----'

You may be wondering what the point is of having blank space at the start,
but it means as the diz is just a text import, it appears at a storming
speed :)

It also means you can fill up the space on either side of the logo with
your own designs etc etc !!!..  E.g. If you've done a file you're really 
proud of, after its been imported, you could edit the diz to have a huge 
arror pointing to it for example :)

AmiExpress filebases also work in this way!


File_ID Packing
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

/X\2.08+ also allow file_id packing.  This is done after a description
is entered in the diz editor.

The scripts are stored in BBS:Scripts/Extract/Pack/  And are in the same
format as the diz extraction scripts.


Free Downloads
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

To make a file a free download, simply go to the file editor and tick FREE!

It's THAT simple! :)

The Free download gadget replaces the (usually) unused LOCK gadget....

If you REALLY need to have a file locked from deletion by co-sysops, then
just have a backup copy away from the BBS, or remove the delete protection
flag using the CLI!  I think the command is..

C:Protect (Filename) -d



Local Uploads
~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Local uploads will take a bit of getting used to!!!

Firstly, add your files using the file editor, or using MagicFile v3.5, but
DON'T enter anything for the description!!!

Then go to the user editor, tick GFD (Magicfile will do this for you) and
then do a local login.

Mp2 will then search through your files and process any descriptions 
needed! :)))

Support utilities will soon be made available so you can just bung all
your files in 1 directory & leave Mp2 to do everything else for you :)

@endnode

@node filescript "Writing Filebase Scripts"

Writing File Extraction Scripts
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Even tho Mp2 can detect 12 differant file types automatically, there may
be times when you want to add a new file type to the list! :)

To do this requires you writing a file script to be placed in 
BBS:Scripts/Extract/Data/...  You need to call the script by the file 
extension name.script...

eg.  A new archiver comes out that saves archives with a .OP8 extension...
To get Mp2 to detect these, you create a script called OP8.Script and Mp2
will recognise the datatype :)  Easy in principle, complex in practice! 

Here's a blank script to get started with! :)

------------------------------------------------------------------------

.key node/a
.bra {
.ket }
; A blank script for example purposes...

c:FailAt 9999		; Don't want this script failing!!!


...  Your script here  ...


SetENV Finished{node} "FIN"
; Needed so STDIO output can terminate :)

------------------------------------------------------------------------

ALL SCRIPTS MUST START AND FINISH WITH THIS !!!!!!!!


The first 3 lines allow the script to recieve the node number from Mp2
so it can set the work directory etc etc.

Scripts can never quit halfway through, so you need the last line of code
to tell Mp2 that you've finished :)

Sounds easy so far, doesn't it :)  Now, your script can do ANYTHING you
want it to do as long as it doesn't try asking the user for any input!



Script Variables
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Mp2 uses enviromental variables to communicate with the file scripts...
The variables sent to the script are listed below...

$UploadedFile{node}	- The FULL path/file name of the file the script
			should be testing.
			
$UploadedReadme{node}	- This is the filename with the .ext removed from
			it and a .readme added, for Aminet .readme decoding!
			eg.  MyFile.lha would become MyFile.readme :)
			
$UploadedDiz{node}	- This is the destination name for any file_id's
			your script may detect!..  These are in a special
			format!..  use BBS:C/ProcessDiz to convert normal
			file_id's to Mp2 standard.
			
			The destination diz name is ALWAYS Diz:filename.diz
			eg. for MyFile.Lha, the diz is stored in 
			Diz:MyFile.Lha.diz
			
If you wish to also gain info about the user who has uploaded the file, then
use the DumpUser command (See Support Utilities for more info)


Returning Data To Mp2
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The following variables are used/set to return information to Mp2 :)

UploadedComment{node}	- Returns a 1 line (59 chars max!) automatic comment
			to be used as the file description!
			This is used by the ProcessDiz util to return aminet
			Short: descriptions, and can also be used by file
			nuker code, eg, if a file is corrupt then set the
			comment to `Corrupted File!' and Mp2 will 
			automatically use this as a description :)
			
CreditDock{node}	- A user automatically gets 1 upload credit for
			each file uploaded in Max's...  If the file is 
			corrupted or on a banned file list, this variable
			can be set to remove the credit :)
			Set with the amount of credits to be docked (Usually 1)

Finished{node}		- Tells Mp2 that your script has finally finished!
			This NEEDS to be set otherwise Mp2 will lock up!
			
MPout{node}		- VERY IMPORTANT ONE!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!
			Any data sent to this variable gets displayed in
			real-time to the Mp2 display!!!
			See below.
			
MPout{node} Explained
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Normally, Mp2 runs the scripts on a quiet display...  If the script wants
to output anything then use re-direction to this variable!.. e.g.

Echo "My file Script" >$MPout{node}

C:DMS Test $UploadedFile{node} >$MPout{node}

All output is in real-time!  Mp2 doesn't wait for the command to finish
before displaying the output! :)))



General Script Writing
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The Mp2 scripts are basically just normal AmigaDOS CLI scripts, so virtually
anything that can be done in a dos script can be used in Mp2!!! :)))

If you don't know much about AmigaDOS scripts, then check on Redrum BBS or
the Aminet for guides on writing them :)))

On the other hand, you may not ever have to write a script!  Any popular
file type will have a script available for it soon! :))

Here's a line by line example for the LHA file script that comes with Mp2!
(This is my personal file script at time of writing!..  The one supplied 
with your copy of Mp2 may well be differant!)

----------------------------------------------

.key node/a
.bra {
.ket }
; Lha Extractor script for MAX's Professional v2.00 :)

c:FailAt 9999		; Don't want this script failing!!!

----------
The above is the normal script startup code
----------

Type BBS:Scripts/MPmacros/LHAFileType.text >$MPout{node}

----------
The Filetype is LHA, so display an ANSI file saying it's LHA :)))
----------

SetEnv UploadedDir{node} "BBS:Scripts/Extract/Node{node}/"
C:CD $UploadedDir{node}

----------
This is a little variable I set, for the work directory to extract to...
It's not NEEDED, but makes life a bit easier for the script! :)
----------

Type BBS:Scripts/MPmacros/TestFile.Txt >$MPout{node}
Type BBS:Scripts/MPmacros/White.macro >$MPout{node}

----------
Display the `Testing File' ANSI message so the user knows what's going on..
The White.macro file is simply a tiny ansi file that just changes the 
writing colour to white :)
----------

C:Lha t $UploadedFile{node} >$MPout{node}

----------
Now test the archive & re-direct the output to the Mp2 display :)
----------


IF NOT WARN
Type BBS:Scripts/MPmacros/BannerStrip.Text >$MPout{node}
C:Lha d $UploadedFile{node} *.displayme

----------
If the archive was tested OK, display a message about stripping any BBS
adverts..  This script only strips #?.displayme files from archives
----------

Type BBS:Scripts/MPmacros/BannerAdd.Text >$MPout{node}
c:lha a $UploadedFile{node} bbs:Scripts/Extract/Important.Redme

----------
These 2 lines add my own BBS advert text file to the archive :)  Alter
the Important.Redme name to your own BBS advert if you wish to add one! :)
----------

Type BBS:Scripts/MPmacros/PleaseWait.Text >$MPout{node}
C:Lha x $UploadedFile{node} file_id.diz $UploadedDir{node}
C:Lha x $UploadedFile{node} $UploadedReadme{node} $UploadedDir{node}

----------
Oki, the script has got this far!  Now try to extract a file_id.diz and
an Aminet .readme file from the archive..  These are then processed by
the following command....
----------

BBS:C/ProcessDiz {node} $UploadedDiz{node}

----------
ProcessDiz checks the node's work directory for both an file_id.diz and
a .readme file...  If there is a file_id, then that will be converted into
Mp2 format and stored.  If it finds a .readme file instead, it will
process that for a Short: description and convert that to an auto file 
comment :)
----------

C:Delete file_id.diz
C:Delete $UploadedReadme{node}

----------
These files aren't needed anymore so just clean the directory up a bit!
----------

ELSE

----------
There's sometimes where the LHA file is corrupted tho.....
----------

Delete $UploadedFile{node}
SetEnv CreditDock{node} "1"

----------
The file is just wasting HD space if it's corrupted, so delete it! :))))
Also remove the upload credit for that file! :)  Change it to "2" to remove 
2 credits & be mean <Grin>
----------

Type BBS:Scripts/MPmacros/ShaggedFile.Text >$MPout{node}
SetEnv UploadedComment{node} "Shagged up LHA archive!  Auto-Nuked By BBS!!!"

----------
Display a nice ANSI file telling the user that the file is shagged :)
And set the return comment so Mp2 doesn't bother asking the user for a file
comment :)
----------

ENDIF

SetENV Finished{node} "FIN"
; Needed so STDIO output can terminate :)

----------
End of script..  Tell Mp2 we've finished for this file!
----------

----------------------------------------------


I know that Mp2 script writing can get complicated at times, but the system
is deliberately low level to provide flexibility in the file handling!

Other file systems expect there to be only a file_id.diz to be detected,
but with the Mp2 system, any concievable file description can be detected
and recognised with the appropriate script!


If your brain has turned to jelly now, then it's time for a ciggy break! :)
or read a book on an easier subject :)  Quantum Mechanics for example :)

@endnode

@node colmsg "COLOUR MESSAGES!!!"

Colour Messages
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Mp2 now supports colour messages on local & echo mail!

There are some limitations to using this feature tho!...  Firstly, Max's
doesn't allow you to use normal ansi in messages, and even if it did then
sending the message across fidonet would strip the ansi codes!

Just follow these steps to create your message :)

1) Create your ansi picture or signiture in a normal ANSI editor.
2) Save as UNCOMPRESSED ANSI!!!  If your ANSI editor won't allow this, then
   change to one that does! :)
3) Convert the file to CSI Ansi using one of supplied utils (See Support
   utilities for more info)
4) Load the resulting text file into a decent text editor :)
5) Make VERY SURE each line of ANSI (Including codes) is shorter than 75
   chars long!  This is important!
   
   
A simple colour change in ANSI can require up to 5 chars of text!, so you
are quite limited in what you can achive :(

Either have a colourful small drawing, or a more basic larger one :)


You need to work with basic, uncompressed ANSI because Max's will reset its
scroll counter whenever it hits a cursor position ANSI code...
Even 1 position code and Max's will just scroll straight to the end of the
message even if it's 100 lines long! :(

I could have removed this, but leaving it in allows for some good effects!

You can even create a full ansi animation (Using compressed ANSI) which
will be displayed in a message!!!

** NOTE IN /X\2.08!

The new /X\2 allows COMPRESSED CSI ANSI in sigs!  But it is not reccomended
unless everyone else on your message network has upgraded!

@endnode

@node ansistand "ANSI Standards"

ANSI Standards
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

There are 2 ANSI standards supported by Mp2! :)

IBM ANSI 
~~~~~~~~

The normal ANSI that Max's and 99% of terminal programs use...
No ther explination is needed on this one, you should know about it by now 
anyway!
	
	 
CSI ANSI
~~~~~~~~

CSI Ansi needs more explination :(..  This is currently only used by Amiga
CLI programs.  The difference between the 2 standards is in the control 
codes...

IBM ansi uses ESC+[ to start an ansi code, which is the normal way of doing
ansi work.  CSI ansi instead uses Ascii code 155 to start an ansi code!

Using CSI Ansi not only means shorter files, but as it relies on using 
printable ascii codes, it can even be used in messages across mail nets!!!

Thankfully, Mp2 converts any CSI Ansi codes into normal IBM Ansi codes 
before displaying.  This means the end user doesn't notice any difference
no matter what computer system they're using!

Please see the support utilities section for converters between the 2 
formats! :)

@endnode

@node autoinsert "The NEW Auto-inserts!"

New Auto-Inserts!
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Yes!  It's true!  My shift key is buggered!...

Anyway, there are 8 new Auto-Inserts supported by Mp2!!!!!!

6 are taken up by the file base - See that section for more info.

These are %" and %! ....  And are one of the biggest features of Mp2!

They allow commands/scripts to be run and the results returned as the 
insert!!!

A quick example you can use on your BBS.text idle screen is...

---------------------------

Currently Available Memory:
%"C:Avail Flush"

---------------------------

And the command between the quotes is executed and anything the command
outputted is display!..  That example would become...

---------------------------
Currently Available memory :
Type  Available    In-Use   Maximum   Largest
chip    1743928    352200   2096128   1642376
fast    5294088   2570232   7864320   4655320
total   7038016   2922432   9960448   4655320
---------------------------


Explination In Detail
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

When Mp2 find a %" insert, it reads in anything between the quotes and
executes that command/script...  Then the command has finished, then anything
the command wrote out is then displayed.

The difference between the 2 inserts is the %! insert adds the current node
number to the end of the command!

As a guide, %" inserts should return as QUICKLY as possible!!!!  Remember
they can be used in normal menu displays so if the user has to wait for your
fancy script to run, they'd probably get pritty cheesed off...

Example uses for script inserts can include...

WWW Style page counters!
Security - Have an insert that lists the last user to access a certain page!
Hypertext!  Have a blank menu with nothing more than a %"C:Type Menu" command
and have other scripts to alter the Menu file with features etc!

The list of possibilites is virtually endless!  Even use them to do special
effects on an ansi sreen! :)

Just use your imagination to think up new scripts :)
@endnode

@node supscript "Support Scripts"

Useful Mp2 Scripts
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

There are 4 scripts that Mp2 runs at regular intervals.  2 are dedicated 
to logins, and 2 are for mail imports & 2 are general purpose scripts.

All 4 are located in BBS:Scripts/


   Login.Script
   PasswordFailed.Script
   
   MailImport.script
   AfterMailImport.script

   UserStart.script
   Logout.script


Login.Script
~~~~~~~~~~~~

This script is run just before the login prompt & can return a user name 
to login with.

A blank script is supplied for you to play with! :)

If the script returns a user name for that node, then Mp2 will automatically
log that person in without asking for a password!

The variable used is deleted before the script is run, so it is pretty secure!

An example below:-

----------------------------------

.key Node/a
.Bra {
.Ket }

SetEnv LoginName3 "Niki Murkett"

----------------------------------

If I used this script, then whenever I logged in on node 3, the script will
automatically log me in :)

This is only a cheat tho!...  The real purpose of this script is to provide
support for CallerID logins, or for nodes on a leased line for example,
where the BBS will KNOW who the user really is :)



PasswordFailed.Script
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

This script is run if a user fails to gain entry after 3 password fails!

The script is run with the user's name in quotes as a param.

An example script could look like...

----------------------------------

.key Name/a
.Bra {
.Ket }

C:Echo >>BBS:LogFiles/Failed.log "User {Name} Failed to gain access!"
C:Date >>BBS:LogFiles/Failed.log

----------------------------------

This script simply logs the name,date and time of the failed access!

You could use more advanced scripts to write an Email to the real person
to inform them of the attemped hack for example :)



MailImport.script
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

This script is run just before Mp2 imports any echo mail! :)

The only reasons for using this script would be to delete certain file
attaches or to change packet names if Mp2 is being run from an external
mail front end like Trapdoor ;)



AfterMailImport.script
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

This is almost identicle to the above script, except it's run after mail
has been imported!  Use for changing packet names etc :)

The mail scripts are only really useful for people running mail nets!


UserStart.script
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

This script is executed just after the user has logged in.  It is run with
a node number & was designed to be used by X-Mail although you can use it
for anything you want.


Logout.script
~~~~~~~~~~~~~

This is run JUST before the Logout.text file is displayed.  It is run with
a node number & can be used for general cleaning up tasks.  It is NOT run
if a user drops carrier, is twitted or exited with %X !


@endnode

@node turbo "Tuuurrrrbbboooooo  Logins!"

Turbo & Scripted Logins
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

One of the most annoying features of Max's was that on local logins, you 
had to enter a password!

WHY?!?!?!?!?!?!?!?

Well you don't anymore! :)))))))))))))))))))))))))))))))

There are 3 types of turbo logins available :-

1) At the login prompt, just hit return to be logged in as the sysop!!!
   (You don't need a login macro on F10 now :))))))) )
   
2) Just enter a user name to be logged in without a password check! :)

3) Scripted logins.  This is the only one that can work for remote users
   and like the first 2, doesn't require a password check!  It's to be used
   for dedicated nodes or CallerID logins for example...
   Please consult the `General Scripts' section for more information.
   

Having a sysop login will make your system more secure!  If you don't make
any remote logins usually, then you can have your password as something
no-one would be able to remember! :)
@endnode

@node menufunc "New Menu Functions!"

New Menu Commands
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Mp2 supports internally up to 50 menu commands now instead of the Max's
limit of 42!

Only 2 new commands are available at present in Mp2, with the rest being
added at a later point via plug-ins!

The new menu functions are:-

43	- Run Door List
44	- Run XIM
45	- Run /X\2 rexx door!


Now to explain them!


Run Door List
~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Door lists are simply an ascii file with a list of doors to be run! :)

They are exactly the same as the introdoor.text file, except you can
specify the list name in the Filename/Name/Dest/Path: gadget!

There are a few restrictions!...  Like the introdoor.text file, you only
specify the door filename relative to Doors:, and the door list *MUST* be
in Doors: for it to work...

An example would be the script I created to link Kewl-Page with Yaan-Chat:-


{Filename: YaanPage.text}

KewlPage/KewlPage +
YaanChat/YaanChat CHAT+


In the menu, this list is run like:-

Key:   Function:  Extra:    Lo Acc:    Hi Acc:	  Filename/Name/Dest/Path:
 C	  43        0          1        10000     YaanPage.text


You could also give users the option to go through your maindoor.text file
again with...

Key:   Function:  Extra:    Lo Acc:    Hi Acc:	  Filename/Name/Dest/Path:
 D	  43        0          1        10000     MainDoor.Text


As you can see, this menu function can have a few good uses! :)



Run XIM
~~~~~~~

This command runs a door designed for the AmiExpress BBS system! :)

Normally these doors (Refered to as XIM's) are totally uncompatable with 
Max's as they use a differant door port system :(

Mp2 Sets up a fake door port to run these XIMs and tries to emulate the
AmiExpress BBS functions.

This isn't easy!  AmiExpress is a conference based system, and as such, a
lot of the door commands have no meaning to a menu based system like Max's!

My advice is to try and find a max's or Mp2 door that does the same job!
but, if your determined to use AmiExpress doors, then here's you to run 
them :)

XIM's are usually configured via tooltypes and have 2 seperate main files.

The first of course is the XIM itself, which you'll place in your Doors: 
directory like usual :)
The second part is an icon that normally goes in BBS:Commands/BBScmd/
The icon is named after the key you press to ru the door!

eg.  W.info  Would run a XIM called Wall (The door name is stored in the 
icon).

Mp2 doesn't use this system, so the icon can be ignored.  Simply tell Mp2
to run the door directly with func 44 :)

eg...

Key:   Function:  Extra:    Lo Acc:    Hi Acc:	  Filename/Name/Dest/Path:
 W	  44        0          1        10000     Doors:LSD-Wall.XIM

And Mp2 will handle the rest by itself! :)

PLEASE NOTE:  The AmiExpress developer information I have access to at this 
point in time isn't up to much :/  So the standard of emulation may not be
too high :(

Saying this however, the emulator managed to run LSD-Wall & several stats
doors I threw at it perfectly, so it can't be that bad! :)))

Also 1 more point, I don't know how, but an emulated XIM runs ** FASTER **
than a XIM running on AmiExpress!!!!!!! :))))))))


/X\2 Rexx Doors
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

/X\2 finally allows you to run arexx scripts!  This system is based around
the popular Cnet system  & are around 95% compatable with current Cnet doors.

For more info look at the seperate Arexx guide :)



@endnode

@node mcimenu "MCI & Arexx Menus"

MCI Menus
~~~~~~~~~

MCI menus are a complex new feature of /X\2 & covers String menus, Param
based doors & Rexx based menu systems.  They are simple to use tho :)

MCI menus begin with the %: insert within the ansi file.  The REST of the
ansi file is NOT displayed!

If you wish to use string menus
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

String menus are stored in a similiar way to the normal max's config.  Start
the line with a % to mark a string command. e.g.

!Who,34,0,0,0,10000,Doors:Who/Who_Online +,

------  Now for a list of those params:-
!Who,34,0,0,0,10000,Doors:Who/Who_Online +,  
P: 1  2 3 4 5 6     7

P1	- This is the string command itself.  It is what the user types in.
P2	- This is the max's menu function you want to run (1-45)
P3	- This is the Extra value.  The same as in the max's menu.
P4	- Flags..  Currently only affect Message & File listings.
P5	- Low Access - Identical to the max's value
P6	- High Access - Same as above.
P7	- This is the same as the path/string gadget in max's.
P8	- There isn't a P8, but you MUST include the , to mark the end of
	  the MCI command.


Currently supported flags are only for file & message listing.  These are:-


Mp2.09 File lister flags

0	= Default - Bring up a list options menu
1	= List new files
2	= Reverse list of files
3	= Forward list of files
4	= Sorted file list
5	= Find a file

Mp2.09 Msg flags!

0	= Default - Bring up a list options menu
1	= New Messages
2	= Forward order
3	= Reverse order
4	= Follow threads
5	= Read individual msg
6	= Search msgs
7	= Read marked msgs



/X\2 has a limit of 40 commands per page.  They are decoded EVERY TIME the
page is displayed so you can use a cgi script to change them if you want :)))

ONLY HAVE 1 COMMAND PER LINE & HAVE A BLANK LINE BETWEEN OPTIONS!

Arexx Menus
~~~~~~~~~~~

To attach an arexx script to a menu, start the MCI menu function with %:
like above, then start a line with:-

*scriptname.rexx"

You MUST end the line with a quote.  If this is the only MCI command then 
/X\2 will revert to the default hotkey menus instead of string menus.

Please look in the seperate rexx guide for more info on writing rexx menus.


CGI Binaries! & Menu Remapping
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

These are 3 new features in Mp2.09 and are processed BEFORE the menuing
system gets access to them.

Please note:-  Any reference to # in a menu ansi FILENAME is now replaced
with the current nodenumber!  e.g.  MainMenu#.text  would become 
MainMenu1.text.


Menu Remapping
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

This is a technique where you can search & replace in a menu ansi before
being displayed :)

In the menu editor go to the `Text filename:' gadget where you normally
have your ansi name.  The new format of this string shound be:-

Menu.ansi?Char,Filename		e.g.  MainMenu.ansi?=,ENV:Section

What this does is loads up the menu ansi into memory & replaces ALL 
occurences of the Char (= in this case) with the CONTENTS of the file 
(ENV:Section here).

This affefts EVERY occurence of the specified char so you should use with 
care & also remember it affects string menus too.  This technique can be
used to create a conference base BBS system within minutes!


Remapping Extra
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Extra remapping is similiar to the standard remapping above with 1 exception.

The format is now:-  Menu.ansi?CharChar2,Filename
  e.g. MainMenu.ansi?=},ENV:Section

The extra char is ANOTHER search & replace, but this time replaces the
specified char with the NODE NUMBER.


ANSI CGI Binaries
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Mp2 uses cgi-bin files in the same way that HTML based systems do :)  A CGI
program is simply a script or exe that takes in params & displays anything
to the current output display  Just like the %" insert!

CGI-bins are just like the %" insert EXCEPT anything it produces are then
used as the current menu!

Format:-

:Bin_name?Param1&Param2&Param3 etc etc
^ 
	All CGI-bins MUST start with a : in the menu!

To simplify things for you, a STANDARD menu is equivilent to:-

:Type?MenuName.ansi




@endnode

@node iconify "The All New Iconify Bar!"

New Iconify Bar
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

OKi, the new iconify bar in Mp2 has been updated beyond belief! :)))

The old bar gave almost useless info like..

1: Niki Murkett - F34


Now, for those with the max's manual emplanted in their brain will know
F34 means the user is in a door...  But which door?!?!?

Also, the window was the WRONG size, so unless you only have a 7 point
font, then the bottom is gonna look wrong :/


These problems are now FIXED :)))

The iconify window now adapts its size to your current workbench font, so
if you have a huge 22pt font then Mp2 will change the window size to suit :)

Also, as some of you have already found out, if the iconify bar would be off
the screen when Max's tries to open it, then it comes up with a crappy
"Can't allocate memory" guru requester :(

Now, Mp2 has a go at opening the window and if it fails because the window
could be off the screen, then it resets the window to the top-left corner
of the screen & tries again :)  This also applies to the clock window :)


Also, instead of displaying F?? where ?? is the menu function, Mp2 now
displays the message in english :))))

1: Niki Murkett - Scanning Mail
1: Niki Murkett - Door - NSA_Wall

Yup, if the user is in a door, it'll even display the door name!!! :)


This idea was inspired (read: Ripped off & enhanced) from an old Max's util
called FuncYpatch by Stoo^DA, but like all his programs, none of them like 
Mp2 in memory (Don't ask why!  Everyone elses code works!).

To add insult to injury really, you can also CHANGE the menu descriptions! :)

If a file exists called ENV:MaxsPro/FunkyNames.Data , then Mp2 will use
that file for the iconify descriptions :)

The file is just a straight ASCII text file, so you should be able to edit
it in virtually anything! :)

Line 0 - Menu func 0  This doesn't exist on the iconify bar, but it means
	 IDLE/At menu and is used by my Who2 who online door :)
Lines 1+ The Max's menu functions from 1-49.  

Just have 1 menu description per line, and pad out the file with blank lines
to make it 50 lines long!.  This will make it easier for plug-ins to add
their own menu descriptions etc :)

There is an example file for you to get going with :)
@endnode

@node doors "Max's Pro 2 Door Support"

Doors
~~~~~

Mp2 has a new door controller :)  It's stilled based on Max's/Paragon,
but with a few alterations!

1) Doors will no longer lock up on multiple local logins!

2) The new door controller has 2 flags to run doors with.


Mp2 Doors
~~~~~~~~~~

If a door says it's for Max's Professional then you need to add a + to the
end of the door name!

eg.

ProDoor +
YaanChat CHAT+

The + must be the last char!  If the door takes no params then have a space
between the door name & the +.

The door will then be sent the Max's Pro control sequence.


Node 0 doors
~~~~~~~~~~~~

In Paragon/Max's, if the user is on a local login, then a door is run as
a node 0 door as standard.

Mp2 no longer does this to prevent 2 doors being run at once on local 
logins! (It will lock the BBS up if you do this normally!)

Some doors (Such as Spin Diz) require node 0 for local uploads, so Mp2 
now has a feature to support it.  Simply add an = to the end of the door
name!

eg.

SimpleDoor =
CrapChat CHAT=

This simply forces Mp2 to revert to the Max's way of running doors.
@endnode

@node miscfeat "Misc features"

Quick Improvements
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Below is a list of improvements in Mp2 that don't really require a 
dedicated page for each one :)


New Message Editor
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The message editor in Mp2 can now cope with messages up to 250 lines long!
Unfortunately, this only applies to the line-by-line editor.  The full
screen editor would need a total re-write to be improved :/


RIP Support
~~~~~~~~~~~

All this feature does is change the hidden text keys from @ and | to 2 new
symbols.  

The @ symbol is now the french franc sign & the | code is now the spanish 
Pts char.

This means you can now use the @ key in menus & chat doors :)))
(@ is required for use by RIP graphics)


Conference Mail
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

You can now use a section for both files & messages at the same time!!!

Tick the File flag in the required section and Mp2 will allow you to write
messages to that section using the normal Read/Write menu commands :)

The ONLY limitation to this (That I know of) is the fact the sections
must keep the same name for both files & mail.


Plug-Ins
~~~~~~~~

Plug-ins are a way of expanding Mp2 without having to wait for a whole
new version to be written!  For example, if there's a minor upgrade to
alter something in the Max's exe, it wouldn't warrant a full upgrade release,
so instead I can just release a plug-in across normal PD channels :)

Plug-ins are stored in BBS:PlugIns/ And are called PlugIn.xx where the xx 
is the number.

If you wish to code your own Plug-ins, then you must contact me for the
required information.


Faster Connections
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Max's v1.54 was pretty sad in the fact it could only handle connect rates
up to 38,400.  Any faster than this and it sets the rate to 300 and usually
gives the "Connected at too slow baud rate" message before kicking the user 
off :(

Mp2 changes the maximum connect speed to 900,000 baud, so fast enough :)
The system can handle 2 Gigabaud, but I don't think Max's can display 
numbers THAT big <Grin>

This means you can finally use ISDN & the new 57.6K modems with Max's :)))


16 Colour ANSI
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Mp2 now supports true 16 colour ANSI graphics!!! :)  This feature is
kicked in automatically when you select a screen with 16 colours (or more)
in the config editor!

The way the system works is if you have a normal 8 colour screen, then Mp2
will still use the Max's colours to display its ANSI, but if in a screen 
mode higher than 8 colours, the whole pallette is changed to the true ANSI
standard.

You may get a `Config has Changed' message when you quit Mp2.  This is
because Mp2 uses the old "Flashing text" sub-system for its own use now, 
and sets/clears that flag automatically.

Max's Professional has never, and will NEVER support flashing text!!!!!

This is a crap feature of Max's, and terminal programs need to run in at
least 32 colours to support it!


Screen Adaptive
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

/X\2 now changes the ansi layout depending on the screen size.  If you
open a screen in 640x512 for example, you now get around 50 lines visible
in the screen :)))))


Mono Mode
~~~~~~~~~

This is more of a bug fix from previous versions of Max's Pro.  Now, whenever
you tick `Monochrome dsply' in the Paths & Opts menu, Mp2 will ignore your
config settings & open the screen in 2 colours.

You may be wondering why the support for black & white text...  It FLIES!!


Clock Hiding
~~~~~~~~~~~~

The crappy clock in Max's can NOW BE HIDDEN!! :)))))))))))

It can't be totally disabled as such, but can now be hidden from display
from the config editor :)

Just make sure that it's covering the ansi display or the status bar before
clicking on HIDE in the config editor :)


File Errors
~~~~~~~~~~~

One of THE most annoying aspects of Max's was in the handling of file 
finding!  It just gave the user a message to inform the sysop!  Or if the 
file was important, it just kicked the user off & didn't leave anything
for the sysop!...

Now, if there's a file that can't be accessed, Mp2 runs a seperate 
requester telling you which file it was looking for :)

The requester is a seperate program stored in BBS:C/ so that Mp2 can still
continue to run like normal :)

The only downside is yo usometimes wake up in the morning to find your 
workbench screen filled with hundreds of requesters :)

@endnode

@node support "Support Utilities"

Support Utils
~~~~~~~~~~~~~

There are several support utilities supplied with Mp2...  They are located
in BBS:C/, all are CLI ONLY & described below :-


ProcessDiz	- Converts normal file_id's to Mp2 format and also checks
		Aminet .readme's for a Short: description.  It currently
		gives preference to File_IDs.
		
		Params: ProcessDiz {node} {destination diz name}
		
CSI_Ansi	- Converts a normal IBM Ansi file to Amiga CSI format.
		Required for colour messages.  Also makes smaller files :)

		Param: CSI_Ansi {filename}
		
IBM_Ansi	- Converts an Amiga CSI ANSI file to IBM format.  Most ANSI
		editors only accept IBM format ansi.
		
		Param: IBM_Ansi {filename}

DumpUserData	- Fills up a LOT of ENV variables with the current users
		data for each node.  Sets the WARN flag if the node has
		no-one online.
		
		Param: DumpUserData {node}
		
ClearUserData	- Removes the ENV variables set up by DumpUserData... To
		be used at the end of any script that uses DumpUserData!
		
		Param: ClearUserData {node}
		

DumpUserData
~~~~~~~~~~~~

When passed a valid node number with a user online, DumpUserData writes out
the following ENV variables for use with scripts.

All are in ASCII.

MPUserName{node}	- The user's name
MPSuburb{node}		- User's Suburb
MPPhone{node}		- User's Phone Number
MPComputer{node}	- Computer the user uses :)
MPComment{node}		- The sysop comment.
MPTimeLeft{node}	- Time remaining in minutes.
MPUserAccess{node}	- Access level.
MPTimeLimit{node}	- User's time limit in minutes.
MPRatio{node}		- User's file ratio
MPLastMessage{node}	- Number of the last message read
MPPageLength{node}	- Page length in lines
MPCalls{node}		- Amount of calls the user has made.
MPMessages{node}	- Amount of messages the user has written
MPUploads{node}		- Amount of files uploaded :)
MPDownloads{node}	- Number of files leached :( 
MPTimeBank{node}	- Amount stored in the time bank in minutes.
MPMaxTimeBank{node}	- Maximum time allowed in the time bank.
MPProtocol{node}	- File Xfer protocol (1 to 6)
MPUserNameNS{node}	- User's name without spaces in...  Could be useful.
MPUserDir{Node}		- Points to the user's current work directory.


@endnode

